@Dymaxion if you decide to start an open hardware business, I can help you avoid shooting the same holes I've shot in my feet.

@kfury answer is too complicated for 140 characters, but if you start a 3D Geneva Convention, invite me.
@nerginer honestly it's probably a mix in the short term.
@nerginer I'm not saying an open source business model is impossible, just that it requires community management skills.
@nerginer We've shot ourselves in the feet more than once, but still focused on products that empower people.
@nerginer now 500 employees strong and we manufacture in BKUSA.
@nerginer in the end I knew what I wanted to make and so we fundraised and I hired excellent people to create great products.
@nerginer if you talk to folks who manage open source projects, I don't think I'm alone in finding it really difficult to manage.
@nerginer I don't think people understand how hard it is to get things developed by strangers for free as a business model.
@nerginer An open hardware business needs a dedicated hardcore dev group that is growing and our group shrunk to just a few devs.
@nerginer especially when the reprap project is out there. Open hardware is easier 4 devs to contribute to when it is a project vs product.
@nerginer I just didn't have the skills to grow the community to work on and contribute and support the open source hardware model.
@nerginer been thinking about this a lot. Lots of reasons the business of open source hardware wasn't working for us.
Other's patents block us from making cool stuff that I wish had prior art. It's a much harder ip world once you pass the maker stage of biz.
It's not the worst thing for a patent 2 b invalidated by prior art. We don't get IP but at least we can make it!
@kfury would be cool but would require everyone in competition to agree and sign on and there may not be enough trust in the industry.
Our primary focus at MakerBot is to empower people to make things. Everything we do is to support that.

Then we don't get ip on that part of the patent.
The really isn't a need for drama, if someone has prior art documented, they just send it to the patent office. If it was indeed prior...
